.Corrections for background are 2.4% and 3.5% at

*By authors*.The cross sections determined in this work
result from the analysis of 18 TOF measurements.
A 1/4-in. thick Li6 glass (NE912) detector
Four BF(3) tubes located in the armored concrete
roof above the uranium target. These detectors are
called central monitors. They give an accurate
normalization of the transmission data with a maximum
dispersion of about 0.5%.
For capture experiments-
the neutron flux is measured with a B-10
ionization chamber.
Two C(6)D(6) liquid scintillators NE230 placed
at 90 degree with respect to the beam axis.
The neutron capture cross section is measured by
detecting the prompt gamma-rays emitted when the
compound nucleus deexcites to its ground state.
A normalization accuracy of about 3%.
The Geel electron linear accelerator
GELINA.
Neutrons were produced by (gamma,N) and
(gamma,fission) reactions induced via bremsstrahlung
from the electron beam hitting a rotating uranium
target.
Two 36 mm water slabs in a beryllium canning
are placed just above and below the target.
The neutrons emitted from the target moderator
assembly are led to the experimental areas along
neutron flight paths.
.The neutron beam diameter is 45 mm.
Time-of-flight technique
.Capture experiment- capture set-up located at 28.67 m
from the neutron source, angle of the flight path
with respect to the moderator is 0 degree.
.Transmission experiment:the neutrons cross a
filter setup and sample dummy at a distance of 23.7 m.
Transmission set-up located at 49.34 m from the
neutron source, angle of the flight path with
respect to the moderator is 9 deg.

.Four samples containing commercial Pb-127I(2) powder
were used. Thin samples were designed to study the
broad resonances at 20.4, 31.2, 37.6 and 45.3 eV.
To increase a physical thickness of samples,
Pb-127I(2) powder was mixed with a large amount of
sulfur-about 1 g/cm2. Parallel measurements were
performed with a liquid sample of Li-127I, specially
designed to study the low neutron energy of the I-127
total cross section. Sample content is -

Reich-moore approximation of the R-matrix
theory, resonance shape analysis with REFIT
and SAMMY codes for the resolved resonance range up
to 10-KeV. Below 5-keV, the resonance parameters were
extracted with a simultaneous analysis of the trans-
mission and capture measurements. Within the 5-10 keV
energy range, the neutron width values and resonance
energies were determined from the transmission data
alone.

The error given for the resonance
energies takes into account the accuracy
of the flight path length, the experimental channel
widths used to map the entire TOF spectra, the
incomplete description of the moderation distance and
the time delay uncertainties.
The quoted errors for the raiation widths are
only the statistical uncertainties provided by the
REFIT-code.
For the neutron widths, the sources of the
systematic errors are mainly the sample thickness,
incomplete description of the resolution function and
the time-dependent background.
The average systematic error affecting the
I-129 neutron width values remains below 3.6%.
The global accuracy of the 127I and 129I mass
fractions is close to 2.5%.
